{"title_page": "Campaign Life Coalition", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Campaign Life Coalition\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| named_after         = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| logo                =\n| logo_size           = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| map                 = \n| map_size            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| map2                = \n| map2_size           = \n| map2_alt            = \n| map2_caption        = \n| abbreviation        = \n| motto               = \n| predecessor         = \n| merged              = \n| successor           = \n| formation           = {{start date and age|1978}}\n| founder             = \n| founding_location   = \n| extinction          = <!-- use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| merger              = \n| type                = \n| tax_id              = <!-- or | vat_id = (for European organizations) -->\n| registration_id     = <!-- for non-profit org -->\n| status              = \n| purpose             = \n| headquarters        = 300-104 Bond Street<br />[[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n| coords              = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|display=inline, title}} -->\n| region              = \n| membership          = \n| membership_year     = \n| leader_title        = National President\n| leader_name         = Jeff Gunnarson\n| leader_title2       = \n| leader_name2        = \n| leader_title3       = \n| leader_name3        = \n| leader_title4       = \n| leader_name4        = \n| board_of_directors  = \n| key_people          = \n| main_organ          = \n| parent_organization = \n| subsidiaries        = \n| secessions          = \n| affiliations        = \n| budget              = \n| budget_year         = \n| revenue             = \n| revenue_year        = \n| disbursements       = \n| expenses            = \n| expenses_year       = \n| endowment           = \n| staff               = \n| staff_year          = \n| volunteers          = \n| volunteers_year     = \n| slogan              = \n| mission             = \n| website             = {{URL|http://www.campaignlifecoalition.com/|campaignlifecoalition.com}}\n| remarks             = \n| formerly            = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n\nThe '''Campaign Life Coalition''' (sometimes shortened to '''Campaign Life''') is a Canadian political lobbyist organization founded in 1978.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Stettner |first1=Shannon |last2=Burnett |first2=Kristin |last3=Hay |first3=Travis |title=Abortion: History, Politics, and Reproductive Justice after Morgentaler |date=2017 |publisher=UBC Press |isbn=978-0-7748-3576-3 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=imhADwAAQBAJ&pg=PA353 |language=en}}</ref> Based in [[Toronto]], the organization advocates for [[social conservatism|socially conservative]] values.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/green-party-anti-abortion-candidates-1.5277682|title=Green candidates say they don't remember past anti-abortion comments|work=CBC|last=Tasker|first=John Paul||last2=Kapelos|first2=Vassy}}</ref> It opposes [[abortion]], [[euthanasia]], [[embryonic stem cell research]], [[assisted reproductive technologies]], [[same-sex marriage]], and [[gender identity]] legislation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kim |first1=Daniel |title=St. Michael's College group attends pro-life demonstration in Ottawa |url=https://thevarsity.ca/2017/06/07/st-michaels-college-group-attends-pro-life-demonstration-in-ottawa/ |work=The Varsity |date=7 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Scala |first1=Francesca |title=Delivering Policy: The Contested Politics of Assisted Reproductive Technologies in Canada |date=2019 |publisher=UBC Press |isbn=978-0-7748-6012-3 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=nRqGDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA159 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Julie |first1=Fish |last2=Kate |first2=Karban |title=LGBT Health Inequalities: International Perspectives in Social Work |date=2015 |publisher=Policy Press |isbn=978-1-4473-2272-6 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=7Yu5BwAAQBAJ&pg=PT296 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Ontario politics ==\nAt the provincial level in [[Ontario]], Campaign Life helped to establish and initially supported the [[New Reform Party of Ontario|Family Coalition Party]] (FCP).<ref>{{cite news|title=Tory courting in Carleton-Gloucester|author=Baer, Nicole|work=The Ottawa Citizen |date=7 May 1988|page=6}}</ref> Following the FCP's name change to the [[New Reform Party of Ontario]] and the election of [[Patrick Brown (politician)|Patrick Brown]] as the new leader of the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario]] in 2015, the CLC seemingly switched support to the Ontario PCs. The CLC endorsed Brown's bid for the leadership, along with other social conservative leadership candidate [[Monte McNaughton]], and released a statement congratulating Brown on his victory.<ref>[https://www.thestar.com/news/queenspark/2015/05/09/patric-brown-wins-ontario-pc-leadership.html \"Patrick Brown wins Ontario PC leadership\"], [[Toronto Star]], May 09 2015.</ref><ref>[https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2015/05/09/ontario-pcs-pick-a-pro-lifer-to-lead-their-rebirth-cohn.html \"Ontario PCs pick a pro-lifer to lead their rebirth\"], [[Toronto Star]], May 09 2015.</ref> The group later became critical of Brown after he publicly announced that he would not repeal the new provincial sex education curriculum changes if he becomes premier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/queenspark/2016/12/27/tory-leader-patrick-brown-feeling-the-squeeze-as-he-tries-to-unify-party-ranks.html|title=Tory Leader Patrick Brown feeling the squeeze as he tries to unify party ranks|last=Ferguson|first=Rob|date=December 27, 2016|website=thestar.com|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=December 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Federal politics==\nCampaign Life endorsed candidates [[Brad Trost]] and [[Pierre Lemieux]] in the [[2017 Conservative Party of Canada leadership election|2017 Conservative leadership election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/canadian-politics/anti-abortion-group-endorses-pro-life-conservative-leadership-candidates-brad-trost-and-pierre-lemieux|title=Anti-abortion group endorses 'pro-life' Conservative leadership candidates Brad Trost and Pierre Lemieux|date=2 September 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n==LifeSiteNews==\nCampaign Life Coalition founded LifeSiteNews in 1997. The website was founded with the intent to promote anti-abortion views.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HRn8CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA172 | title = The Changing Voice of the Anti-Abortion Movement | last1 = Saurette | first1 = Paul | first2 = Kelly | last2 = Gordon | publisher = University of Toronto Press | year = 2016 | isbn = 9781442615694 | location = | page = 172 | language = en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Snopes, LifeSiteNews is \"a known purveyor of misleading information.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/aclu-director-resigns-over-transgender-bathroom-policy/ | title = FACT CHECK: ACLU Director Resigns Over Transgender Bathroom Policy | website = Snopes.com | date = June 3, 2016 | first = Kim | last = Lacapria | language = en-US | access-date = May 30, 2019}}</ref> The Associated Press described the website as \"ultraconservative.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://apnews.com/c7786459105b41639033c183e1a6ddb5 | title = Sanctions, sex abuse and silence: A primer on the pope saga | last = Winfield | first = Nicole | date=September 9, 2018 | website = AP NEWS | agency = [[Associated Press]] | access-date = May 30, 2019 | via = apnews.com}}</ref> In May 2019, Philip Pullela, in a Reuters article, wrote that the website \"often is a platform for attacks on [<nowiki/>[[Pope Francis]]].\"<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pope-heresy-idUSKCN1S73KE | title = Conservatives want Catholic bishops to denounce pope as heretic | date = May 1, 2019 | website = reuters.com | agency = [[Reuters]] | access-date=May 30, 2019 | language = en | first = Philip | last = Pullella}}</ref> The LGBT magazine ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'' has described LifeSiteNews as an anti-LGBT outlet, and criticised it for articles blaming [[Catholic Church sexual abuse cases|clerical sex abuse]], including that of children, on homosexuality.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.advocate.com/media/2018/8/20/meet-lifesite-news-one-most-anti-lgbtq-online-outlets | title = Meet LifeSite News, One of the Most Anti-LGBTQ Online Outlets | date = August 20, 2018 | website = [[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] | via = advocate.com | language = en | access-date=May 30, 2019}}</ref> Research has shown no evidence that sexual orientation affects the likelihood of a person's abusing children.<ref name=herekmolest>[[Gregory M. Herek]]: [http://psychology.ucdavis.edu/rainbow/html/facts_molestation.html Facts About Homosexuality and Child Molestation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100419022239/http://psychology.ucdavis.edu/rainbow/HTML/facts_molestation.html |date=19 April 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.apa.org/helpcenter/sexual-orientation.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101111062219/http://www.apa.org/helpcenter/sexual-orientation.aspx|archive-date=2010-11-11|title=Sexual orientation, homosexuality, and bisexuality |publisher=American Psychological Association |accessdate=2010-11-30 }}</ref>\n\nA Catholic priest, [[Raymond Gravel]], filed a lawsuit in [[Quebec]] against the website in 2011 for defamation.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.catholic.org/news/international/americas/story.php?id=40380 | title = Quebec Priest sues LifeSiteNews for Defamation  - Americas - International - News - Catholic Online|last=Gyapong|first=Deborah | agency = [[Canadian Catholic News]] | work = [[The B.C. Catholic|The B.C. Catholic Newspaper]] | date = February 16, 2011 | via = www.catholic.org | access-date= July 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/controversial-priests-lawsuit-against-lifesitenews-advances | title = Controversial Priest\u2019s Lawsuit Against LifeSiteNews Advances | work = [[National Catholic Register]] | agency = [[Catholic News Agency]] | via = ncregister.com | date = February 21, 2013 | first = Carl | last = Bunderson | access-date = May 30, 2019}}</ref> Subsequently, Gravel died of lung cancer on August 11, 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/father-raymond-gravel-outspoken-social-activist-dies-1.2733315 |title=Father Raymond Gravel, outspoken social activist, dies | work = [[CBC News]] |date=August 11, 2014 |accessdate=September 18, 2014 }}</ref> In 2013, the lawsuit was allowed to advance to trial by a [[Quebec]] court.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/activist-priest-raymond-gravel-preached-gospel-of-tolerance/article19997653/ | title = Activist priest Raymond Gravel preached gospel of tolerance | date = August 11, 2014 | work = [[The Globe and Mail]] | first = Fred | last = Langan | access-date = July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWriting in ''[[The American Conservative]]'', [[Rod Dreher]] described ''LifeSiteNews'', together with ''[[Church Militant (website)|Church Militant]]'' and ''One Peter Five'', as \"tabloid Catholic journalism\". He commended these sites for reporting on scandal and corruption more openly than establishment conservative Catholic outlets.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dreher |first1=Rod |title=In Praise Of Tabloid Catholic Journalism |url=https://www.theamericanconservative.com/dreher/in-praise-of-tabloid-catholic-journalism/ |date=January 6, 2020|accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=The American Conservative}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Church Militant (website)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.campaignlifecoalition.com/}}\n*[http://www.lifesite.net/ LifeSiteNews official website]\n\n[[Category:1978 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1978]]\n[[Category:Anti-abortion organizations in Canada]]\n[[Category:Conservatism in Canada]]\n[[Category:Right-wing politics in Canada]]\n[[Category:Organizations that oppose same-sex marriage]]\n[[Category:Lobbying organizations in Canada]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Year of establishment missing]]\n[[Category:Christian political organizations]]\n[[Category:Christian organizations based in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Campaign Life Coalition\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| named_after         = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| logo                =\n| logo_size           = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| map                 = \n| map_size            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| map2                = \n| map2_size           = \n| map2_alt            = \n| map2_caption        = \n| abbreviation        = \n| motto               = \n| predecessor         = \n| merged              = \n| successor           = \n| formation           = {{start date and age|1978}}\n| founder             = \n| founding_location   = \n| extinction          = <!-- use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| merger              = \n| type                = \n| tax_id              = <!-- or | vat_id = (for European organizations) -->\n| registration_id     = <!-- for non-profit org -->\n| status              = \n| purpose             = \n| headquarters        = 300-104 Bond Street<br />[[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n| coords              = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|display=inline, title}} -->\n| region              = \n| membership          = \n| membership_year     = \n| leader_title        = National President\n| leader_name         = Jeff Gunnarson\n| leader_title2       = \n| leader_name2        = \n| leader_title3       = \n| leader_name3        = \n| leader_title4       = \n| leader_name4        = \n| board_of_directors  = \n| key_people          = \n| main_organ          = \n| parent_organization = \n| subsidiaries        = \n| secessions          = \n| affiliations        = \n| budget              = \n| budget_year         = \n| revenue             = \n| revenue_year        = \n| disbursements       = \n| expenses            = \n| expenses_year       = \n| endowment           = \n| staff               = \n| staff_year          = \n| volunteers          = \n| volunteers_year     = \n| slogan              = \n| mission             = \n| website             = {{URL|http://www.campaignlifecoalition.com/|campaignlifecoalition.com}}\n| remarks             = \n| formerly            = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n\nThe '''Campaign Life Coalition''' (sometimes shortened to '''Campaign Life''') is a Canadian political lobbyist organization founded in 1978.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Stettner |first1=Shannon |last2=Burnett |first2=Kristin |last3=Hay |first3=Travis |title=Abortion: History, Politics, and Reproductive Justice after Morgentaler |date=2017 |publisher=UBC Press |isbn=978-0-7748-3576-3 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=imhADwAAQBAJ&pg=PA353 |language=en}}</ref> Based in [[Toronto]], the organization advocates for [[social conservatism|socially conservative]] values.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/green-party-anti-abortion-candidates-1.5277682|title=Green candidates say they don't remember past anti-abortion comments|work=CBC|last=Tasker|first=John Paul||last2=Kapelos|first2=Vassy}}</ref> It opposes [[abortion]], [[euthanasia]], [[embryonic stem cell research]], [[assisted reproductive technologies]], [[same-sex marriage]], and [[gender identity]] legislation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kim |first1=Daniel |title=St. Michael's College group attends pro-life demonstration in Ottawa |url=https://thevarsity.ca/2017/06/07/st-michaels-college-group-attends-pro-life-demonstration-in-ottawa/ |work=The Varsity |date=7 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Scala |first1=Francesca |title=Delivering Policy: The Contested Politics of Assisted Reproductive Technologies in Canada |date=2019 |publisher=UBC Press |isbn=978-0-7748-6012-3 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=nRqGDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA159 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Julie |first1=Fish |last2=Kate |first2=Karban |title=LGBT Health Inequalities: International Perspectives in Social Work |date=2015 |publisher=Policy Press |isbn=978-1-4473-2272-6 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=7Yu5BwAAQBAJ&pg=PT296 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Ontario politics ==\nAt the provincial level in [[Ontario]], Campaign Life helped to establish and initially supported the [[New Reform Party of Ontario|Family Coalition Party]] (FCP).<ref>{{cite news|title=Tory courting in Carleton-Gloucester|author=Baer, Nicole|work=The Ottawa Citizen |date=7 May 1988|page=6}}</ref> Following the FCP's name change to the [[New Reform Party of Ontario]] and the election of [[Patrick Brown (politician)|Patrick Brown]] as the new leader of the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario]] in 2015, the CLC seemingly switched support to the Ontario PCs. The CLC endorsed Brown's bid for the leadership, along with other social conservative leadership candidate [[Monte McNaughton]], and released a statement congratulating Brown on his victory.<ref>[https://www.thestar.com/news/queenspark/2015/05/09/patric-brown-wins-ontario-pc-leadership.html \"Patrick Brown wins Ontario PC leadership\"], [[Toronto Star]], May 09 2015.</ref><ref>[https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2015/05/09/ontario-pcs-pick-a-pro-lifer-to-lead-their-rebirth-cohn.html \"Ontario PCs pick a pro-lifer to lead their rebirth\"], [[Toronto Star]], May 09 2015.</ref> The group later became critical of Brown after he publicly announced that he would not repeal the new provincial sex education curriculum changes if he becomes premier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/queenspark/2016/12/27/tory-leader-patrick-brown-feeling-the-squeeze-as-he-tries-to-unify-party-ranks.html|title=Tory Leader Patrick Brown feeling the squeeze as he tries to unify party ranks|last=Ferguson|first=Rob|date=December 27, 2016|website=thestar.com|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=December 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Federal politics==\nCampaign Life endorsed candidates [[Brad Trost]] and [[Pierre Lemieux]] in the [[2017 Conservative Party of Canada leadership election|2017 Conservative leadership election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/canadian-politics/anti-abortion-group-endorses-pro-life-conservative-leadership-candidates-brad-trost-and-pierre-lemieux|title=Anti-abortion group endorses 'pro-life' Conservative leadership candidates Brad Trost and Pierre Lemieux|date=2 September 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n==LifeSiteNews==\nCampaign Life Coalition founded LifeSiteNews in 1997. The website was founded with the intent to promote anti-abortion views.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HRn8CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA172 | title = The Changing Voice of the Anti-Abortion Movement | last1 = Saurette | first1 = Paul | first2 = Kelly | last2 = Gordon | publisher = University of Toronto Press | year = 2016 | isbn = 9781442615694 | location = | page = 172 | language = en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Snopes, LifeSiteNews is \"a known purveyor of misleading information.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/aclu-director-resigns-over-transgender-bathroom-policy/ | title = FACT CHECK: ACLU Director Resigns Over Transgender Bathroom Policy | website = Snopes.com | date = June 3, 2016 | first = Kim | last = Lacapria | language = en-US | access-date = May 30, 2019}}</ref> The Associated Press described the website as \"ultraconservative.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://apnews.com/c7786459105b41639033c183e1a6ddb5 | title = Sanctions, sex abuse and silence: A primer on the pope saga | last = Winfield | first = Nicole | date=September 9, 2018 | website = AP NEWS | agency = [[Associated Press]] | access-date = May 30, 2019 | via = apnews.com}}</ref> In May 2019, Philip Pullela, in a Reuters article, wrote that the website \"often is a platform for attacks on [<nowiki/>[[Pope Francis]]].\"<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pope-heresy-idUSKCN1S73KE | title = Conservatives want Catholic bishops to denounce pope as heretic | date = May 1, 2019 | website = reuters.com | agency = [[Reuters]] | access-date=May 30, 2019 | language = en | first = Philip | last = Pullella}}</ref> The LGBT magazine ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'' has described LifeSiteNews as an anti-LGBT outlet, and criticised it for articles blaming [[Catholic Church sexual abuse cases|clerical sex abuse]], including that of children, on homosexuality.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.advocate.com/media/2018/8/20/meet-lifesite-news-one-most-anti-lgbtq-online-outlets | title = Meet LifeSite News, One of the Most Anti-LGBTQ Online Outlets | date = August 20, 2018 | website = [[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] | via = advocate.com | language = en | access-date=May 30, 2019}}</ref> Research has shown no evidence that sexual orientation affects the likelihood of a person's abusing children.<ref name=herekmolest>[[Gregory M. Herek]]: [http://psychology.ucdavis.edu/rainbow/html/facts_molestation.html Facts About Homosexuality and Child Molestation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100419022239/http://psychology.ucdavis.edu/rainbow/HTML/facts_molestation.html |date=19 April 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.apa.org/helpcenter/sexual-orientation.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101111062219/http://www.apa.org/helpcenter/sexual-orientation.aspx|title=Sexual orientation, homosexuality, and bisexuality |publisher=American Psychological Association |accessdate=2010-11-30 }}</ref>\n\nA Catholic priest, [[Raymond Gravel]], filed a lawsuit in [[Quebec]] against the website in 2011 for defamation.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.catholic.org/news/international/americas/story.php?id=40380 | title = Quebec Priest sues LifeSiteNews for Defamation  - Americas - International - News - Catholic Online|last=Gyapong|first=Deborah | agency = [[Canadian Catholic News]] | work = [[The B.C. Catholic|The B.C. Catholic Newspaper]] | date = February 16, 2011 | via = www.catholic.org | access-date= July 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/controversial-priests-lawsuit-against-lifesitenews-advances | title = Controversial Priest\u2019s Lawsuit Against LifeSiteNews Advances | work = [[National Catholic Register]] | agency = [[Catholic News Agency]] | via = ncregister.com | date = February 21, 2013 | first = Carl | last = Bunderson | access-date = May 30, 2019}}</ref> Subsequently, Gravel died of lung cancer on August 11, 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/father-raymond-gravel-outspoken-social-activist-dies-1.2733315 |title=Father Raymond Gravel, outspoken social activist, dies | work = [[CBC News]] |date=August 11, 2014 |accessdate=September 18, 2014 }}</ref> In 2013, the lawsuit was allowed to advance to trial by a [[Quebec]] court.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/activist-priest-raymond-gravel-preached-gospel-of-tolerance/article19997653/ | title = Activist priest Raymond Gravel preached gospel of tolerance | date = August 11, 2014 | work = [[The Globe and Mail]] | first = Fred | last = Langan | access-date = July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWriting in ''[[The American Conservative]]'', [[Rod Dreher]] described ''LifeSiteNews'', together with ''[[Church Militant (website)|Church Militant]]'' and ''One Peter Five'', as \"tabloid Catholic journalism\". He commended these sites for reporting on scandal and corruption more openly than establishment conservative Catholic outlets.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dreher |first1=Rod |title=In Praise Of Tabloid Catholic Journalism |url=https://www.theamericanconservative.com/dreher/in-praise-of-tabloid-catholic-journalism/ |date=January 6, 2020|accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=The American Conservative}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Church Militant (website)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.campaignlifecoalition.com/}}\n*[http://www.lifesite.net/ LifeSiteNews official website]\n\n[[Category:1978 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1978]]\n[[Category:Anti-abortion organizations in Canada]]\n[[Category:Conservatism in Canada]]\n[[Category:Right-wing politics in Canada]]\n[[Category:Organizations that oppose same-sex marriage]]\n[[Category:Lobbying organizations in Canada]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Year of establishment missing]]\n[[Category:Christian political organizations]]\n[[Category:Christian organizations based in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Genericusername57", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLifeSiteNews:fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campaign_Life_Coalition"}
{"title_page": "Quebrada Grande, Barranquitas, Puerto Rico", "text_new": "{{short description|Barrio of Puerto Rico}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n<!-- Basic info  -------------- -->\n| official_name            = Quebrada Grande\n| other_name               =\n| native_name              =\n| nickname                 =\n| settlement_type          = Barrio\n| motto                    =\n<!-- images and maps  --------- -->\n| image_skyline            = \n| imagesize                =\n| image_caption            = \n| image_flag               = \n| flag_size                =\n| image_seal               = \n| seal_size                =\n| image_blank_emblem       =\n| blank_emblem_type        =\n| blank_emblem_size        =\n| image_map                = Quebrada Grande, Barranquitas, Puerto Rico locator map.png\n| pushpin_map              = Puerto Rico#Caribbean\n| pushpin_map_caption = Quebrada Grande, Barranquitas, Puerto Rico\n| coordinates              = {{Coord|18.1988682|-66.280488000000005|display=inline, title|format=dms}}\n<!-- Location ---------------- -->\n| subdivision_type1        = [[Commonwealth (U.S. insular area)|Commonwealth]]\n| subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Puerto Rico}}\n| subdivision_type2        = [[List of municipalities in Puerto Rico|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2        = {{flagicon image|Flag of Barranquitas.svg}} [[Barranquitas, Puerto Rico|\nBarranquitas]]<!-- Politics --------------- -->\n| government_footnotes     =\n| government_type          =\n| leader_title             = \n| leader_name              = \n| leader_title1            = \n| leader_name1             =\n| leader_title2            =\n| leader_name2             =\n| established_title        = \n| established_date         = \n| established_title2       = \n| established_date2        =\n| established_title3       = \n| established_date3        =\n<!-- Area    ------------------- -->\n| area_magnitude           = 1 E7\n| unit_pref                = Imperial\n| area_footnotes           =\n| area_total_km2           = \n| area_land_km2            = \n| area_water_km2           = \n| area_total_sq_mi          =  \n| area_land_sq_mi          =  \n| area_water_sq_mi         =  \n| area_water_percent       = \n| area_urban_km2           =\n| area_urban_sq_mi         =\n| area_metro_km2           =\n| area_metro_sq_mi         =\n| area_blank1_title        =\n| area_blank1_km2          =\n| area_blank1_sq_mi        =\n<!-- Population   --------------------- -->\n| population_as_of         = 2010\n| population_footnotes     = \n| population_note          = Source: 2010 Census\n<!-- USE OF COMMA FOR THE FIELD BELOW IS OPTIONAL -------- -->\n| population_total         = 3217 \n| population_density_km2   = \n<!-- DO NOT USE COMMAS FOR THE POPULATION DENSITY BELOW -- -->\n| population_density_sq_mi =  \n| population_metro         = \n| population_density_metro_km2     =\n| population_density_metro_sq_mi   =\n| population_urban                 =\n| population_density_urban_km2     =\n| population_density_urban_sq_mi   =\n| population_blank1_title          =\n| population_blank1                =\n| population_density_blank1_km2    =\n| population_density_blank1_sq_mi  =\n<!-- General information  ------------- -->\n| timezone                 = [[Atlantic Time Zone|AST]]\n| utc_offset               = &minus;4\n| timezone_DST             = \n| utc_offset_DST           = \n| latd =\n| longd =\n| elevation_footnotes      = \n| elevation_m              = \n| elevation_ft             = 1972\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others ------ -->\n| postal_code_type         =\n| postal_code              =\n| area_code                = \n| blank_name               = \n| blank_info               = \n| blank1_name              = \n| blank1_info              = \n| website                  = \n| footnotes                =\n}}\n'''Quebrada Grande''' is a [[Barrios of Puerto Rico|barrio]] in the municipality of [[Barranquitas, Puerto Rico]]. Its population in 2010 was 3,217.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pic\u00f3 |first1=Rafael |last2=Buitrago de Santiago |first2=Zayda |last3=Berrios |first3=Hector H. |title=Nueva geograf\u00eda de Puerto Rico: f\u00edsica, econ\u00f3mica, y social, por Rafael Pic\u00f3. Con la colaboraci\u00f3n de Zayda Buitrago de Santiago y H\u00e9ctor H. Berrios. |url=https://archive.org/details/nuevageografad00pic/page/247|publisher=San Juan Editorial Universitaria, Universidad de Puerto Rico,1969}}<br>- {{cite book|author=Gwillim Law|title=Administrative Subdivisions of Countries: A Comprehensive World Reference, 1900 through 1998| url =https://books.google.com/books?id=nXCeCQAAQBAJ|accessdate=25 December 2018|date=20 May 2015|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-0447-3|page=300}}<br>- {{cite book|title=Puerto Rico:2010:population and housing unit counts.pdf | url = https://permanent.access.gpo.gov/gpo35934/cph-2-53.pdf|year=2010|publisher=U.S. Dept. of Commerce, Economics and Statistics Administration, U.S. Census Bureau}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe [[United States]] took control of Puerto Rico from [[Spain]] in the aftermath of the [[Spanish-American War]] under the terms of the [[Treaty of Paris (1898)|Treaty of Paris of 1898]]. In 1899, the United States conducted its first [[census]] of Puerto Rico, finding that the population of Quebrada Grande barrio was 931.<ref name=\"OfficeSanger1900\">{{cite book|author1=Joseph Prentiss Sanger|author2=Henry Gannett|author3=Walter Francis Willcox|title=Informe sobre el censo de Puerto Rico, 1899, United States. War Dept. Porto Rico Census Office|url=https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog|year=1900|publisher=Imprenta del gobierno|page=[https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog/page/n256 165]| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==Special community==\nSince 2001 when law 1-2001 was passed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lexjuris.com/lexlex/Leyes2001/lex2001001.htm|title=Leyes del 2001|website=Lex Juris Puerto Rico|language=es|accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref> measures have been taken to identify and address the high levels of poverty and the lack of resources and opportunities affecting specific communities in Puerto Rico. Initially there were 686 places that made the list.<ref name=\"wordpress.com\">{{cite web|url=https://cpprbib.wordpress.com/biblioteca-virtual/guias-tematicas/comunidades-especiales/comunidades-especiales-de-puerto-rico/|title=Comunidades Especiales de Puerto Rico|date=8 August 2011|language=es|accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref> By 2008, there were 742 places on the list of {{lang|es|Comunidades especiales de Puerto Rico}}. The places on the list are barrios, communities, sectors, or neighborhoods and in 2004, Quebrada Grande made the list.<ref name=\"wordpress.com\"/> In 2017, Jes\u00fas V\u00e9lez Vargas, the director of the Special Communities of Puerto Rico program stated that the program was evolving with more ways to help the residents of these so-called [[Social exclusion|marginalized]] communities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/locales/nota/evolucionaelproyectodecomunidadesespeciales-2294682/|title=Evoluciona el proyecto de Comunidades Especiales|date=24 February 2017|newspaper=El Nuevo Dia|language=es|accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elvocero.com/gobierno/ya-es-ley-oficina-para-el-desarrollo-socioecon-mico-y/article_54769072-382d-5156-9acf-9e8c0b4f4d82.html|title=Ya es ley Oficina para el Desarrollo Socioecon\u00f3mico y Comunitario|first=Por|last=ElVocero.com|newspaper=El Vocero de Puerto Rico|language=es|accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of communities in Puerto Rico]]\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{gnis|2415877}}\n\n[[Category:Barrios of Barranquitas, Puerto Rico]]\n\n\n{{PuertoRico-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Barrio of Puerto Rico}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n<!-- Basic info  -------------- -->\n| official_name            = Quebrada Grande\n| other_name               =\n| native_name              =\n| nickname                 =\n| settlement_type          = Barrio\n| motto                    =\n<!-- images and maps  --------- -->\n| image_skyline            = \n| imagesize                =\n| image_caption            = \n| image_flag               = \n| flag_size                =\n| image_seal               = \n| seal_size                =\n| image_blank_emblem       =\n| blank_emblem_type        =\n| blank_emblem_size        =\n| image_map                = Quebrada Grande, Barranquitas, Puerto Rico locator map.png\n| pushpin_map              = Puerto Rico#Caribbean\n| pushpin_map_caption = Quebrada Grande, Barranquitas, Puerto Rico\n| coordinates              = {{Coord|18.1988682|-66.280488000000005|display=inline, title|format=dms}}\n<!-- Location ---------------- -->\n| subdivision_type1        = [[Commonwealth (U.S. insular area)|Commonwealth]]\n| subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Puerto Rico}}\n| subdivision_type2        = [[List of municipalities in Puerto Rico|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2        = {{flagicon image|Flag of Barranquitas.svg}} [[Barranquitas, Puerto Rico|\nBarranquitas]]<!-- Politics --------------- -->\n| government_footnotes     =\n| government_type          =\n| leader_title             = \n| leader_name              = \n| leader_title1            = \n| leader_name1             =\n| leader_title2            =\n| leader_name2             =\n| established_title        = \n| established_date         = \n| established_title2       = \n| established_date2        =\n| established_title3       = \n| established_date3        =\n<!-- Area    ------------------- -->\n| area_magnitude           = 1 E7\n| unit_pref                = Imperial\n| area_footnotes           =\n| area_total_km2           = \n| area_land_km2            = \n| area_water_km2           = \n| area_total_sq_mi          =  \n| area_land_sq_mi          =  \n| area_water_sq_mi         =  \n| area_water_percent       = \n| area_urban_km2           =\n| area_urban_sq_mi         =\n| area_metro_km2           =\n| area_metro_sq_mi         =\n| area_blank1_title        =\n| area_blank1_km2          =\n| area_blank1_sq_mi        =\n<!-- Population   --------------------- -->\n| population_as_of         = 2010\n| population_footnotes     = \n| population_note          = Source: 2010 Census\n<!-- USE OF COMMA FOR THE FIELD BELOW IS OPTIONAL -------- -->\n| population_total         = 3217 \n| population_density_km2   = \n<!-- DO NOT USE COMMAS FOR THE POPULATION DENSITY BELOW -- -->\n| population_density_sq_mi =  \n| population_metro         = \n| population_density_metro_km2     =\n| population_density_metro_sq_mi   =\n| population_urban                 =\n| population_density_urban_km2     =\n| population_density_urban_sq_mi   =\n| population_blank1_title          =\n| population_blank1                =\n| population_density_blank1_km2    =\n| population_density_blank1_sq_mi  =\n<!-- General information  ------------- -->\n| timezone                 = [[Atlantic Time Zone|AST]]\n| utc_offset               = &minus;4\n| timezone_DST             = \n| utc_offset_DST           = \n| latd =\n| longd =\n| elevation_footnotes      = \n| elevation_m              = \n| elevation_ft             = 1972\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others ------ -->\n| postal_code_type         =\n| postal_code              =\n| area_code                = \n| blank_name               = \n| blank_info               = \n| blank1_name              = \n| blank1_info              = \n| website                  = \n| footnotes                =\n}}\n'''Quebrada Grande''' is a [[Barrios of Puerto Rico|barrio]] in the municipality of [[Barranquitas, Puerto Rico]]. Its population in 2010 was 3,217.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pic\u00f3 |first1=Rafael |last2=Buitrago de Santiago |first2=Zayda |last3=Berrios |first3=Hector H. |title=Nueva geograf\u00eda de Puerto Rico: f\u00edsica, econ\u00f3mica, y social, por Rafael Pic\u00f3. Con la colaboraci\u00f3n de Zayda Buitrago de Santiago y H\u00e9ctor H. Berrios. |url=https://archive.org/details/nuevageografad00pic/page/247|publisher=San Juan Editorial Universitaria, Universidad de Puerto Rico,1969}}<br>- {{cite book|author=Gwillim Law|title=Administrative Subdivisions of Countries: A Comprehensive World Reference, 1900 through 1998| url =https://books.google.com/books?id=nXCeCQAAQBAJ|accessdate=25 December 2018|date=20 May 2015|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-0447-3|page=300}}<br>- {{cite book|title=Puerto Rico:2010:population and housing unit counts.pdf | url = https://permanent.access.gpo.gov/gpo35934/cph-2-53.pdf|year=2010|publisher=U.S. Dept. of Commerce, Economics and Statistics Administration, U.S. Census Bureau}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe [[United States]] took control of Puerto Rico from [[Spain]] in the aftermath of the [[Spanish-American War]] under the terms of the [[Treaty of Paris (1898)|Treaty of Paris of 1898]]. In 1899, the United States conducted its first [[census]] of Puerto Rico, finding that the population of Quebrada Grande barrio was 931.<ref name=\"OfficeSanger1900\">{{cite book|author1=Joseph Prentiss Sanger|author2=Henry Gannett|author3=Walter Francis Willcox|title=Informe sobre el censo de Puerto Rico, 1899, United States. War Dept. Porto Rico Census Office|url=https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog|year=1900|publisher=Imprenta del gobierno|page=[https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog/page/n256 165]| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==Special community==\nSince 2001 when law 1-2001 was passed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lexjuris.com/lexlex/Leyes2001/lex2001001.htm|title=Leyes del 2001|website=Lex Juris Puerto Rico|language=es|accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref> measures have been taken to identify and address the high levels of poverty and the lack of resources and opportunities affecting specific communities in Puerto Rico. Initially there were 686 places that made the list.<ref name=\"wordpress.com\">{{cite web|url=https://cpprbib.wordpress.com/biblioteca-virtual/guias-tematicas/comunidades-especiales/comunidades-especiales-de-puerto-rico/|title=Comunidades Especiales de Puerto Rico|date=8 August 2011|language=es|accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref> By 2008, there were 742 places on the list of {{lang|es|Comunidades especiales de Puerto Rico}}. The places on the list are barrios, communities, sectors, or neighborhoods and in 2004, Quebrada Grande made the list.<ref name=\"wordpress.com\"/> In 2017, Jes\u00fas V\u00e9lez Vargas, the director of the Special Communities of Puerto Rico program stated that the program was evolving with more ways to help the residents of these so-called [[Social exclusion|marginalized]] communities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/locales/nota/evolucionaelproyectodecomunidadesespeciales-2294682/|title=Evoluciona el proyecto de Comunidades Especiales|date=24 February 2017|newspaper=El Nuevo Dia|language=es|accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elvocero.com/gobierno/ya-es-ley-oficina-para-el-desarrollo-socioecon-mico-y/article_54769072-382d-5156-9acf-9e8c0b4f4d82.html|title=Ya es ley Oficina para el Desarrollo Socioecon\u00f3mico y Comunitario|first=Por|last=ElVocero.com|newspaper=El Vocero de Puerto Rico|language=es|accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{gnis|2415877}}\n\n[[Category:Barrios of Barranquitas, Puerto Rico]]\n\n\n{{PuertoRico-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "The Eloquent Peasant", "label": "safe", "comment": "add List of communities in Puerto Rico to See also section", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quebrada_Grande,_Barranquitas,_Puerto_Rico"}
